            },
            "answer_text": "I\u2019ve read with amusement the answer to this question that put forth the idea that this phrase did not exist prior to 1968. I personally used it in high school and I graduated in 1965. The first time I heard it spoken was by my friend Fred Y. We had just come across the word cunnilingus, probably because we were nerdy teenagers poring over an article in Playboy, and Fred came up with what I thought was a clever bit of wordplay. Subsequently I heard other people use it and was surprised to find it so widely accepted. I shouldn\u2019t have been so surprised really. This is one of those natural, easily deduced word associations, like \u201csmart feller\u201d and \u201cfart smeller\u201d. In the case of a new and unusual word like cunnilingus, it\u2019s reasonable for us to mentally search for similar, but more familiar, sounds. Cunning and linguist, both known words, flash immediately to mind and combined, provide a satisfying pun like response that pleases our ears. We revel in our own cleverness! I file this one under \u201cGreat minds think alike . . . and idiots seldom differ!\u201d ",
